observation.p:
When we row reduce the augmented matrix for a homogeneous system of linear equations, the last column will be zero throughout the row reduction process.  We saw this in the last :
      \amat{1 3 4 0; 2 -1 2 0; 1 0 1 0}
      So it is not really necessary to write augmented matrices when solving homogeneous systems.

specialcase.p:
Consider the following matrix in reduced row echelon form:
A = \mat{1 0 -8 -7; 0 1 4 3; 0 0 0 0}.
The matrix equation Ax=0 corresponds to the system of equations

  \syseq{x_1 \+ \. - 8x_3 - 7x_4 = 0;
  \. \+ x_2 + 4x_3 + 3x_4 = 0\rlap.}

We can write the parametric form as follows:
\syseq{
x_1 = 8x_3 + 7x_4;
x_2 = -4x_3 - 3x_4;
x_3 = x_3;
x_4 = \. \+ x_4\rlap.}

We wrote the redundant equations x_3=x_3 and x_4=x_4 in order to turn the above system into a vector equation:
x = \vec{x_1 x_2 x_3 x_4} = x_3\vec{8 -4 1 0} + x_4\vec{7 -3 0 1}.
This vector equation is called the parametric vector form of the solution set.
Since x_3 and x_4 are allowed to be anything, this says that the solution set is the set of all linear combinations of \vec{8 -4 1 0} and \vec{7 -3 0 1}.  In other words, the solution set is
\Span\left\{\vec{8 -4 1 0},\;\vec{7 -3 0 1}\right\}.

solution.p:
We row reduce (without augmenting, as suggested in the above ):
        \mat{1 -3; 2 -6} \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
        \mat{1 -3; 0 0}.

        This corresponds to the single equation x_1 - 3x_2=0.  We write the parametric form including the redundant equation x_2=x_2:
        \syseq{x_1 = 3x_2; x_2 = x_2\rlap.}
        We turn these into a single vector equation:
        x = \vec{x_1 x_2} = x_2\vec{3 1}.
        This is the parametric vector form of the solution set.
        Since x_2 is allowed to be anything, this says that the solution set is the set of all scalar multiples of {3\choose 1}, otherwise known as
        \Span\left\{\vec{3 1}\right\}.
        We know how to draw the picture of a span of a vector: it is a line.  Therefore, this is a picture of the the solution set:


\begin{tikzpicture}
  \path[clip] (-6,-2) rectangle (6,2);
  \draw[grid lines] (-6,-2) grid (6,2);
  \draw[thick] (-6,0) -- (6,0);
  \draw[thick] (0,-2) -- (0,2);
  \draw[seq4] (-6,-2) -- node[pos=.4, above left=1pt, whitebg, thin border]
   {$Ax=0$} (6,2);
  \draw[vector, seq-green] (0,0) -- (3,1);
\end{tikzpicture}

subsection.p:
Since there were two variables in the above , the solution set is a subset of \R^2.  Since one of the variables was free, the solution set is a line:


\begin{tikzpicture}
  \path[clip] (-6,-2) rectangle (6,2);
  \draw[grid lines] (-6,-2) grid (6,2);
  \draw[thick] (-6,0) -- (6,0);
  \draw[thick] (0,-2) -- (0,2);
  \draw[seq4] (-6,-2) -- node[pos=.4, above left=1pt, whitebg, thin border]
   {$Ax=0$} (6,2);
  \draw[vector, seq-green] (0,0) -- (3,1);
\end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
We row reduce (without augmenting, as suggested in the above ):
        \mat{1 -1 2; -2 2 -4} \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
        \mat{1 -1 2; 0 0 0}.

        This corresponds to the single equation x_1 - x_2 + 2x_3 = 0.  We  write the parametric form including the redundant equations x_2=x_2 and x_3=x_3:
        \syseq{x_1 = x_2 - 2x_3; x_2 = x_2; x_3 = \. \+ x_3\rlap.}
        We turn these into a single vector equation:
        x = \vec{x_1 x_2 x_3} = x_2\vec{1 1 0} + x_3\vec{-2 0 1}.
        This is the parametric vector form of the solution set.
        Since x_2 and x_3 are allowed to be anything, this says that the solution set is the set of all linear combinations of \vec{1 1 0} and \vec{-2 0 1}.  In other words, the solution set is
        \Span\left\{\vec{1 1 0},\;\vec{-2 0 1}\right\}.
        We know how to draw the span of two noncollinear vectors in \R^3: it is a plane.  Therefore, this is a picture of the solution set:


\begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz]
  \path[clip, resetxy] (-6,-4) rectangle (6,4);

  \def\v{(1, 1, 0)}
  \def\w{(-2, 0, 1)}

  \node[coordinate] (X) at \v {};
  \node[coordinate] (Y) at \w {};

  \draw (0,0,-3) -- (0,0,0);

  \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), transformxy]
    \path[clip] (-5, 0) -- (-5, -5) -- (5, -5) -- (5, 0) -- cycle;
    \fill[seq4!30, nearly opaque] (-3,-2) rectangle (3,2);
    \draw[step=1cm, seq4, very thin] (-3,-2) grid (3,2);
  \end{scope}

  \begin{scope}[transformxy]
    \fill[white, nearly opaque] (-3, -3) rectangle (3, 3);
    \draw[grid lines] (-3, -3) grid (3, 3);
    \draw[->] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
    \draw[->] (0,-3) -- (0,3);
  \end{scope}

  \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), transformxy]
    \path[clip] (-5, 0) -- (-5, 5) -- (5, 5) -- (5, 0) -- cycle;
    \fill[seq4!30, nearly opaque] (-3,-2) rectangle (3,2);
    \draw[step=1cm, seq4, very thin] (-3,-2) grid (3,2);
  \end{scope}

  \draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,3);

  \draw[vector, seq1] (0,0,0) -- \v;
  \draw[vector, seq2] (0,0,0) -- \w;
  \draw[thin, densely dotted] \w -- \projxy\w;

  \node[seq4, anchor=south east] at (-3,-2.5,.5) {$Ax=0$};

  \point at (0,0,0);

\end{tikzpicture}

We row reduce the associated augmented matrix:
        \amat{1 -3 -3; 2 -6 -6} \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
        \amat{1 -3 -3; 0 0 0}.

        This corresponds to the single equation x_1 - 3x_2 = -3.  We can write the parametric form as follows:
        \syseq{x_1 = 3x_2 - 3; x_2 = x_2 + 0\rlap.}
        We turn the above system into a vector equation:
        x = \vec{x_1 x_2} = x_2\vec{3 1} + \vec{-3 0}.
        This vector equation is called the parametric vector form of the solution set.
        We write the solution set as
        \Span\left\{\vec{3 1}\right\} + \vec{-3 0}.
        Here is a picture of the the solution set:


\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes]
  \draw[grid lines] (-6,-2) grid (6,3);
  \path[clip] (-6,-2) rectangle (6,3);
  \draw (-6,0) -- (6,0);
  \draw (0,-2) -- (0,3);
  \draw[seq2] (-6,-2) -- node[pos=.6,below right=1pt,whitebg] {$Ax=0$} (6,2);
  \draw[seq4] (-6,-1) -- node[pos=.7,above left=1pt,whitebg] {$Ax=b$} (6,3);
  \point (a) at (-3,0);
  \draw[vector, seq1] (a) -- (0,1);
  \draw[->, vector, seq3] (0,0) -- node[pos=.3,above] {$p$} (a);
  \point at (0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

subsection.p:
In the above , the solution set was all vectors of the form
    x = \vec{x_1 x_2} = x_2\vec{3 1} + \vec{-3 0}
    where x_2 is any scalar.  The vector p = {-3\choose 0} is also a solution of Ax=b: take x_2=0.  We call p a particular solution.

In the solution set, x_2 is allowed to be anything, and so the solution set is obtained as follows: we take all scalar multiples of {3\choose 1} and then add the particular solution p = {-3\choose 0} to each of these scalar multiples.  Geometrically, this is accomplished by first drawing the span of {3\choose 1}, which is a line through the origin (and, not coincidentally, the solution to Ax=0), and we translate, or push, this line along p = {-3\choose 0}.  The translated line contains p and is parallel to \Span\{{3\choose 1}\}: it is a translate of a line. 


\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes]
  \draw[grid lines] (-6,-2) grid (6,3);
  \path[clip] (-6,-2) rectangle (6,3);
  \draw (-6,0) -- (6,0);
  \draw (0,-2) -- (0,3);
  \draw[seq2] (-6,-2) -- node[pos=.6,below right=1pt,whitebg] {$Ax=0$} (6,2);
  \draw[seq4] (-6,-1) -- node[pos=.7,above left=1pt,whitebg] {$Ax=b$} (6,3);
  \point (a) at (-3,0);
  \draw[vector, seq1] (a) -- (0,1);
  \draw[->, vector, seq3] (0,0) -- node[pos=.3,above] {$p$} (a);
  \point at (0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
We row reduce the associated augmented matrix:
        \amat{1 -1 2 1; -2 2 -4 -2} \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
        \mat{1 -1 2 1; 0 0 0 0}.

        This corresponds to the single equation x_1 - x_2 + 2x_3 = 1.  We can write the parametric form as follows:
        \syseq{x_1 = x_2 - 2x_3 + 1; x_2 = x_2 \+ \. + 0; x_3 = \. \+ x_3 + 0\rlap.}
        We turn the above system into a vector equation:
        x = \vec{x_1 x_2 x_3} = x_2\vec{1 1 0} + x_3\vec{-2 0 1} + \vec{1 0 0}.
        This vector equation is called the parametric vector form of the solution set.
        Since x_2 and x_3 are allowed to be anything, this says that the solution set is the set of all linear combinations of \vec{1 1 1} and \vec{-2 0 1}, translated by the vector p = \vec{1 0 0}.  This is a plane which contains p and is parallel to \Span\left\{\vec{1 1 0},\;\vec{-2 0 1}\right\}: it is a translate of a plane.  We write the solution set as
        \Span\left\{\vec{1 1 0},\;\vec{-2 0 1}\right\} + \vec{1 0 0}.
        Here is a picture of the solution set:


\begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz]
  \path[clip, resetxy] (-6,-4) rectangle (6,4);

  \def\v{(1, 1, 0)}
  \def\w{(-2, 0, 1)}
  \def\pp{(1, 0, 0)}

  \node[coordinate] (X) at \v  {};
  \node[coordinate] (Y) at \w  {};
  \node[coordinate] (P) at \pp {};

  \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), , xshift=-.8cm, yshift=-.5cm, transformxy]
    \path[clip] (-5, 0) -- (-5, -5) -- (5, -5) -- (5, 0) -- cycle;
    \fill[seq4!30, nearly opaque] (-3,-2) rectangle (3,2);
    \draw[step=1cm, seq4, very thin] (-3,-2) grid (3,2);
  \end{scope}

  \draw (0,0,-3) -- (0,0,0);

  \begin{scope}[transformxy]
    \fill[white, nearly opaque] (-2, -3) rectangle (4, 3);
    \draw[grid lines] (-2, -3) grid (4, 3);
    \draw[->] (-2,0) -- (4,0);
    \draw[->] (0,-3) -- (0,3);
  \end{scope}

  \draw[->] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,3);

  \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), xshift=-.8cm, yshift=-.5cm, transformxy]
    \path[clip] (-5, 0) -- (-5, 5) -- (5, 5) -- (5, 0) -- cycle;
    \fill[seq4!30, nearly opaque] (-3,-2) rectangle (3,2);
    \draw[step=1cm, seq4, very thin] (-3,-2) grid (3,2);
  \end{scope}

  \draw[vector, seq1] \pp -- ($(X) + (P)$);
  \draw[vector, seq2] \pp -- ($(Y) + (P)$);
  \draw[thin, densely dotted] ($(Y) + (P)$) -- (-1, 0, 0);
  \draw[vector, seq3, opacity=.5] (0,0,0) -- node[below right, thin border] {$p$} \pp;

  \node[seq4, anchor=south east] at (-2,-2.5,.5) {$Ax=b$};

  \point at \pp;
  \point at (0,0,0);

\end{tikzpicture}

According to the , this is supposed to be a translate of a span by p.  Indeed, we saw in the first  that the only solution of Ax=0 is the trivial solution, i.e., that the solution set is the one-point set \{0\}.  The solution set of the inhomogeneous equation Ax=b is
        \{0\} + \vec{-1 -1 1}.
        Note that \{0\} = \Span\{0\}, so the homogeneous solution set is a span.


\begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz, x={(-.3cm,-.5cm)}, z={(0cm,1.3cm)}, thin border nodes]
  \path[clip, resetxy] (-6,-4) rectangle (6,4);

  \def\v{(-1, -1, 1)}

  \begin{scope}[transformxy]
    \fill[white, nearly opaque] (-3, -3) rectangle (3, 3);
    \draw[grid lines] (-3, -3) grid (3, 3);
    \draw[->] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
    \draw[->] (0,-3) -- (0,3);
  \end{scope}

  \draw[vector, seq3] (0,0,0) -- \v;

  \draw[thin, densely dotted] \v -- (-1, -1, 0);
  \point[fill=seq-violet, "$Ax=b\,$" {above, seq-violet}] at \v;
  \point[fill=seq-blue, "$Ax=0$" {below right, seq-blue}] at (0,0,0);

\end{tikzpicture}
